Datasets and schemas¶

There are 4 tables that we will use:

  1. alaska_probe_period_temp_cal_vmc.csv AND alberta_probe_period_temp_cal_vmc.csv - both contain the soil moisture and temperature (hourly) data for the sites of Sag River, Alaska, USA, and Red Earth Creek in Alberta, Canada (respectively) that were recorded by the data loggers
    • probe_id - used as a foreign identifier to access the other tables to get relevant info about a particular probe (corresponds to the probe column in the probe coeff table)
    • timestamp - datetime
    • record - unique record number/ID
    • batt_V_min - battery voltage measured in $V$ for the data logger
    • pa_us_avg_1 - probe period for sample in microseconds, $\mu s$
    • pa_us_avg_2 - probe period for sample in microseconds, $\mu s$
    • pa_us_avg_3 - probe period for sample in microseconds, $\mu s$
    • pa_us_avg_4 - probe period for sample in microseconds, $\mu s$
    • t109_c_avg - temperature of the soil measured by probe in degrees celsius
    • probe1_cal - (%) calculated volumetric moisture content from probe-specific calibration model
    • probe2_cal - (%) calculated volumetric moisture content from probe-specific calibration model
    • probe3_cal - (%) calculated volumetric moisture content from probe-specific calibration model
    • probe4_cal - (%) calculated volumetric moisture content from probe-specific calibration model

Note that both tables for Alaska and Alberta have the exact same schema.

soil_moisture_model_coefficients.csv - contains the model coefficients for calibrating soil moisture loggers for each soil type. Volumetric moisture content is calculated as follows:

\begin{align} VMC = A\cdot x^{2} + B\cdot x + C \end{align}

where $x$ is the probe period

  • Soil_type - type of soil
  • A - coefficient for variable A in models
  • B - coefficient for variable B in models
  • C - coefficient for variable C in models

Clean the data¶

Change data type¶

In [9]:
# alaska and alberta have the correct data types for all columns, except probe_id - needs to be int later
# probe_coeff and soil_coeff have a few object columns that need to be changed to string

probe_coeff_obj_cols = list(probe_coeff.select_dtypes(include='object'))
soil_coeff_obj_cols = list(soil_coeff.select_dtypes(include='object'))

def change_data_type(df, cols, data_type):
    for col in cols:
        df[col] = df[col].astype(data_type)
    return df

probe_coeff = change_data_type(probe_coeff, probe_coeff_obj_cols, "string")
soil_coeff = change_data_type(soil_coeff, soil_coeff_obj_cols, "string")

Handle missing data¶

The data guide states that all numeric missing values are denoted as -9999 and all the text missing values are denoted by "NA". Looking at df.info() will tell us the proportions of the missing values denoted as null, but this is not representative of the other missing valies denoted as -9999 or "NA". So lets use this information to look at the entire distribution of missing data and decide if we should drop rows/columns with those missing values, or use an imputation method.

Alaska and alberta dataframes are the only ones that have missing values denoted by null. Probe_coeff and soil_coeff don't have any nulls, but we will check all four dataframes for the other inconsistent/missing values.

In [15]:
def check_missing_data(df, data_type):
    
    '''
    This function will check the dataframe for missing values based on the criteria explained in the sections 
    above (i.e., -9999, NA, or null)
    
    Args:
        df (Pandas Dataframe) : the dataframe we are checking for missing and inconsistent values
              data_type (str) : the datatype we will filter the df (since some missing values are denoted 
                                differently for numerical and text columns)
                                
    Returns: 
        dictionary : the proportions of TOTAL missing values (null and filled in with -9999 or "NA") of each column
    
    '''
    
    if data_type == "numerical":
        # get all columns with int data types
        cols = df.loc[:, (df.dtypes == "float64") | (df.dtypes == "int64")].columns 
        
        # count how many rows contain either a null or -9999 for numerical values 
        
        proportions = np.array(
            np.round(
                (((df[cols].isnull()) | (df[cols] == -9999)).sum()/len(df))*100, 
                    5
                )
            )
        return pprint.pformat(dict(zip(cols,  proportions)))
    
    elif data_type == "string": # change to string later
        cols = df.loc[:, (df.dtypes == "string")].columns 
        # count how many rows contain either a null or NA for text values 

        proportions = np.array(
            np.round(
                (((df[cols].isnull()) | (df[cols] == "NA")).sum()/len(df))*100, 
                    5
                )
            )
        return pprint.pformat(dict(zip(cols,  proportions)))

The distributions of missing data (null, -9999, and NA) are less than 1% for alaska and between 10-12% for alberta. For both dataframes, we will drop the rows that are part of a consecutive group of nulls and keep the nulls that appear singularly.

In [17]:
alberta_consec_nulls = alberta['probe_id'].isnull() & alberta['probe_id'].shift().isnull()
alaska_consec_nulls = alaska['probe_id'].isnull() & alaska['probe_id'].shift().isnull()

alberta_cleaned = alberta[~alberta_consec_nulls]
alaska_cleaned = alaska[~alaska_consec_nulls]

def extract_date(df):
    
    df['min'] = df['time_stamp'].dt.minute
    df['hour'] = df['time_stamp'].dt.hour
    df['day'] = df['time_stamp'].dt.day
    df['month'] = df['time_stamp'].dt.month
    df['year'] = df['time_stamp'].dt.year

    return df

According to the guide, the table probe_coeff has a column called probe that represents a unique ID for each of the probes made up of 2 important numbers. The ID is in the form of <left number> - <right number> where the left number before the hyphen corresponds to the sensor ID, and the right number after the hyphen corresponds to the columns pa_us_avg_* and probe*_cal in the alberta and alaska dataframes.

For ease of joining these tables, we will manipulate the probe column in probe_coeff to extract these 2 unique ID values and create separte columns for them.

# location should be a mid point between alaska and alberta

def find_midpoint(x1, y1, x2, y2):
    '''
    These values are a mean of the latitudes and longitudes
    
    x1 : mean of the alaska latitudes
    y1 : mean of the alberta latitudes
    x2 : mean of the alaska longitudes
    y2 : mean of the alberta longitudes
    
    '''
    
    return [(x1+y1)/2, (x2+y2)/2]

midpoint = find_midpoint(
    x1=np.mean(probe_coeff[probe_coeff['area']=='Alaska'].latitude),
    y1=np.mean(probe_coeff[probe_coeff['area']=='Alberta'].latitude),
    x2=np.mean(probe_coeff[probe_coeff['area']=='Alaska'].longitude),
    y2=np.mean(probe_coeff[probe_coeff['area']=='Alberta'].longitude)
)

all_map = folium.Map(location=midpoint, tiles="OpenTopoMap", zoom_start=4)

for lat, long in zip(probe_coeff.latitude, probe_coeff.longitude):

    folium.Marker(location=[lat, long]).add_to(all_map)

def find_peaks_region(df):
    all_peaks = []
    for i in range(1,5):
        peaks, _ = find_peaks(df[f'probe{i}_cal'], height=0)
        if len(peaks) == 0:
            all_peaks.append(-1)
        else:
            all_peaks.append(max(peaks))
    
    return all_peaks
In [42]:
def plot_avg_with_max(df, time_unit):
    peaks = find_peaks_region(df)
    fig = plt.figure()
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    
    for num in range(1,5):

        ax.plot(df[time_unit], df[f'probe{num}_cal'], label=f'probe{num}_cal')
        if peaks[num-1] != -1:
            x = df[time_unit][peaks[num-1]]
            y = np.array(df[df[time_unit]==x][f'probe{num}_cal'])
            ax.plot(
                x, y,
                'o'
            )
            ax.annotate(f"({x}, {round(y[0], 3)})", (x, y))

    if time_unit == 'month':
        plt.xlabel("month")
        plt.ylabel("average calculated volumetric soil moisture, %")
        plt.title("Monthly averaged volumetric soil moisture")
        
    elif time_unit == 'year':
        plt.xlabel("year")
        plt.ylabel("average calculated volumetric soil moisture, %")
        plt.title("Yearly averaged volumetric soil moisture")
    plt.legend()

def moisture_soil_avg_df(region_df, probe_df):
    
    '''
    Creates a pandas df that joins the region specific dataframe with the dataframe with the probe coefficient 
    and soil specific percentages.
    
    Arguments: 
    region_df (Pandas df) : region specific dataframe with volumetric soil content
     probe_df (Pandas df) : dataframe with information about probes and soil percentages 
     
    Returns: 
    df (Pandas df) : joined region and probe dataframes with averages probe specific columns (averages probe 1-4)
                     into one
    '''
    
    df = pd.merge(region_df, probe_df, on = ['probe_id', 'record'], how='inner')
    
    probe_period_cols = ['pa_us_avg_1', 'pa_us_avg_2', 'pa_us_avg_3', 'pa_us_avg_4']
    volumetric_cols = ['probe1_cal', 'probe2_cal', 'probe3_cal', 'probe4_cal']
    
    string_cols = list(df.select_dtypes(include='string').columns)
    extra_cols = ['A', 'B', 'C', 'latitude', 'longitude']
    
    # calc the averages of probe specific cols
    df['probe_period_avg'] = df[probe_period_cols].mean(axis=1)
    df['volume_avg'] = df[volumetric_cols].mean(axis=1)
    
    # drop the extra cols
    df = df.drop(np.array(probe_period_cols+volumetric_cols+string_cols+extra_cols), axis = 1)

    return df

Alberta: Higher volumetric soil content is associated with
